{
  "doc_id": "52293",
  "text": "Some years ago, we published reports about the high gain of GaAs photoresistors at low illumination levels due to the optical modulation of depleted regions under the GaAs surface [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . This gain , derived from the photo-FET devices that the naked surface and the bottom interface with the substrate created in GaAs epilayers, is inversely proportional to the illumination power impinging on the photresistor thus, it is orders of magnitude greater than the \"photoconductive\" gain due to the conductivity modulation of the GaAs bulk by photogenerated electron-hole pairs at low illumination levels. Therefore, the changes Δ in the resistance of any GaAs photoresistor under weak illumination power reflect modulations in the channel crosssection of this two-terminal device (2TD) rather than conductivity modulations of their inner material as it is commonly assumed.",
